--> Read verses 33-37

So the topic in this section is oaths and the words relate to the concepts of honesty and integrity

Integrity is the quality of being honest and having strong moral principles that you consistently adhere to, regardless of whether anyone is watching

Honesty is the moral virtue of being truthful, sincere, and trustworthy in our words and actions and refusing to deceive, steal, or cheat

Pillars of honesty:
- Truthfulness: Consistently speaking and representing facts accurately without distortion or intent to mislead
- Authenticity: Acting in a way that aligns with your genuine self, rather than putting up a false front to impress others
- Reliability: Being someone whose promises and commitments can be completely counted on


Interity:

A oath back then was something that involved Gods name, or a substitute for it, to guarantee the truth of one's statements

People at the time would use God's name as a token to seal a promise

With dishonesty being rampant and integrity being rare, people would use an oath to give more credibility to their promises

The idea of adding a qualifier to what we are saying to declare honesty in a way is saying that if we don't qualify what we say, it might not be true

It's like when people say "to be honest". Makes you wonder that if they don't say that, are they lying?

I've heard things like "I swear to God" "I swear on my mother"

Jesus is telling his followers that they should be so honest that their words can be believed without requiring an oath

Don't swear by anything, just be honest

No exceptions or fine print that allows you to wiggle out of doing what you say. 

At the time, qualifying one's word with an oath could be used as a loophole to get out of something

Jesus is saying to his followers that they should be known for their integrity and therefore not need to enhance their promises with an oath

We only need to swear by somthing if our word can't hold itself

Become trustworthy by not breaking people's trust





Summary

At the time, people were invoking Gods name and other things to guarantee the truth of their words

Jesus is telling people to be true to their word so there is no requirement for an oath

Jesus is telling his followers to be honest and have integrity

To mean yes when they say yes, to mean no when they say no

In our house we have a rule to always keep our promises

Trust is built on our reputation for keeping our word

I strive to never make promises I'm not certain I can make good on

As Christians we should strive to be known for our honesty so that our word is good enough to be trusted because we are worthy of being trusted based on our past behaviour

Our word is our bond. If we say we will do something, we do it, period. no oaths required

Refelction questions:
- Are you being honest with God?
- Are you being honest with yourself. If you decide to do something, do you follow through?
- Are you being honest with others? With people in your family, business or social network?

- Are you known as a trustworthy person who's word is upheld? Do you keep your promises? 

Things to think about

